Machines Need Everything Defined
The machine has no common sense. You define everything:
void setup() {
  pinMode(13, OUTPUT);  // "Pin 13 is an output — configure it once"
}

void loop() {
  digitalWrite(13, HIGH); // "set Pin 13 HIGH (5V)"
}

Forget pinMode? The pin defaults to input — your LED won’t light.


Precision is the machine’s strength. Common sense is yours.

Exercise 11 — Q1: How Many Pins?
Read this sketch line by line, top to bottom:
void setup() {
  pinMode(13, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(12, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  digitalWrite(13, HIGH); delay(1000);
  digitalWrite(13, LOW);
  digitalWrite(12, HIGH); delay(500);
  digitalWrite(12, LOW);
}
(recall) How many pins does this script use?

Answer: 2 — Pin 13 and Pin 12.

Exercise 11 — Q2: Input or Output?
pinMode(13, OUTPUT);
pinMode(12, OUTPUT);
(recall) Are the pins inputs or outputs?

Answer: Both are outputs (OUTPUT). The Arduino drives these pins HIGH or LOW.

Exercise 11 — Q3: Describe the Script
digitalWrite(13, HIGH); delay(1000);
digitalWrite(13, LOW);
digitalWrite(12, HIGH); delay(500);
digitalWrite(12, LOW);
(apply) Describe in plain language what this script does, step by step.

Answer: Pin 13 turns ON → waits 1 second → turns OFF. Then Pin 12 turns ON → waits 0.5 seconds → turns OFF. The loop repeats this forever.

Exercise 11 — Q5: Blink 3 Times
(design) Modify it: How would you make Pin 13’s LED blink 3 times before Pin 12 turns on?

Answer:
for (int i = 0; i &lt; 3; i++) {
    digitalWrite(13, HIGH); delay(500);
    digitalWrite(13, LOW); delay(500);
}

digitalWrite(12, HIGH); delay(500);
digitalWrite(12, LOW);

Build #1 — Arduino Code
// Define each LED pin
const int red    = 2;
const int yellow = 3;
const int green  = 4;

void setup() {
  pinMode(red, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(yellow, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(green, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  digitalWrite(red, HIGH);    delay(5000);   // Red ON for 5 s
  digitalWrite(red, LOW);
  digitalWrite(yellow, HIGH); delay(2000);   // Yellow ON for 2 s
  digitalWrite(yellow, LOW);
  digitalWrite(green, HIGH);  delay(5000);   // Green ON for 5 s
  digitalWrite(green, LOW);
}

Build #2 — Arduino Code
const int ldrPin = A0;
const int ledPin = 12;

int DARK_THRESHOLD = 600;  // 0–1023; tune this in class

void setup() {
  pinMode(ledPin, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  int ldrReading = analogRead(ldrPin);      // 0 = bright, 1023 = dark (counter-intuitive!)
  if (ldrReading &gt; DARK_THRESHOLD) {
    digitalWrite(ledPin, HIGH);             // dark (high value) → LED ON
  } else {
    digitalWrite(ledPin, LOW);              // bright (low value) → LED OFF
  }
  delay(100);
}

Exercise 13 — Q4: Stabilising Noisy Readings
(design) The sensor reading can bounce slightly (noise). How could you use multiple readings or delay() to make the response more stable?

Answer: Average several readings before deciding:
long sum = 0;
for (int i = 0; i &lt; 5; i++) sum += analogRead(A0);
int ldrReading = sum / 5;
Or only switch the LED if the condition holds for several consecutive loops — prevents flickering from brief spikes.

Writing the Tinkercad Code
Once wired, let’s write the code to spin the motor. We use the exact same digitalWrite commands we learned for LEDs.
void setup() {
  pinMode(9, OUTPUT);  // IN1
  pinMode(10, OUTPUT); // IN2
  pinMode(11, OUTPUT); // ENA (Speed)
}

void loop() {
  // Spin Forward at half speed
  digitalWrite(9, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(10, LOW);
  analogWrite(11, 150); 
  delay(1000);

  // Stop completely
  digitalWrite(9, LOW);
  digitalWrite(10, LOW);
  analogWrite(11, 0);
  delay(1000);
}

The Base Code
To drive a car, we must manage 4 pins simultaneously.
// Define our pins
#define ML_Ctrl 4    // Left Direction
#define ML_PWM 5     // Left Speed
#define MR_Ctrl 2    // Right Direction
#define MR_PWM 6     // Right Speed

void setup() {
  pinMode(ML_Ctrl, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(ML_PWM, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(MR_Ctrl, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(MR_PWM, OUTPUT);
}

Functions: Organizing Logic
Typing digitalWrite four times just to move forward is tedious. In C++, we can create custom functions to bundle commands together.
void car_front() {
  digitalWrite(ML_Ctrl, HIGH);
  analogWrite(ML_PWM, 150); // Set speed (0-255)
  digitalWrite(MR_Ctrl, HIGH);
  analogWrite(MR_PWM, 150);
}

void car_Stop() {
  analogWrite(ML_PWM, 0);
  analogWrite(MR_PWM, 0);
}

Driving the Car
Now, our loop() becomes very simple and easy to read!
void loop() {
  car_front();
  delay(2000); // Drive for 2 seconds

  car_Stop();
  delay(1000); // Wait 1 second
}






Instructor Checkpoint


Upload this code to your Arduino. Put the car on the floor. Does it move forward? If it spins in a circle, one of your motors is wired backward! How can you fix it? (Hint: Swap the physical wires, or swap HIGH and LOW in the code).

Exercise: Turning
How does a tank turn? It spins its tracks in opposite directions!
(Apply): Write the code for a turnRight() function.

Solution: To turn Right, the Left wheels must go Forward, and the Right wheels must go Backward.
void car_right() {
  digitalWrite(ML_Ctrl, HIGH); // Left Forward
  analogWrite(ML_PWM, 150);

  digitalWrite(MR_Ctrl, LOW); // Right Backward
  analogWrite(MR_PWM, 150);
}

