The Logic: Decoding
Once you have your codes, we use a switch statement to decide what to do.
#include &lt;IRremote.hpp&gt;

#define IR_RECEIVE_PIN 2

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  IrReceiver.begin(IR_RECEIVE_PIN, ENABLE_LED_FEEDBACK);
  // ... your motor setup from Part 4 ...
}

void loop() {
  if (IrReceiver.decode()) {
    unsigned long cmd = IrReceiver.decodedIRData.decodedRawData;
    Serial.println(cmd, HEX); // See the code in the monitor

    handleCommand(cmd); // Custom function to move the car

    IrReceiver.resume(); // Ready for next signal
  }
}

Creating Your Controller
Integrate the functions you wrote in Part 4!
void handleCommand(unsigned long cmd) {
  switch (cmd) {
    case 0xFF18E7: // Example code for UP
      forward();
      break;
    case 0xFF4AB5: // Example code for DOWN
      backward();
      break;
    case 0xFF38C7: // Example code for OK
      stopCar();
      break;
    // Add Left and Right!
  }
}






Pro Tip


If your car keeps moving even after you let go of the button, it’s because the IR signal was only sent once. You might need a “Stop” button or a timer!

🔥 Bonus: Choreograph a Dance
You’ve mastered forward, backward, left, and right. Now let’s be creative!
Challenge: Write a loop() that makes the car perform a dance routine:

Use at least 4 different moves
Use delay() to control the timing and rhythm
Give your routine a name (e.g., robotDisco())







Hint


Think of it like choreography. What happens if you spin first, then go forward, then spin the other way?
void robotDisco() {
  forward();   delay(500);
  turnRight(); delay(300);
  backward();  delay(500);
  turnLeft();  delay(300);
  stopCar();
}

