SoftwareSerial: Creating a Second Mouth
The Arduino Uno only has one main communication port (Pins 0 and 1), which it uses to talk to your computer via USB.
If we attach the Bluetooth module to Pins 0 and 1, we can’t upload code!
Instead, we use SoftwareSerial to create a “virtual” communication port on Pins 2 and 3.
#include &lt;SoftwareSerial.h&gt;

// RX on Arduino (Pin 2) connects to TX on Bluetooth
// TX on Arduino (Pin 3) connects to RX on Bluetooth
SoftwareSerial BTSerial(2, 3); // RX, TX

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);   // Talk to Computer
  BTSerial.begin(9600); // Talk to Phone App
}

Reading the Signal
We need the Arduino to listen continuously. If the phone sends an 'F', we turn on the motors.
void loop() {
  // If the Bluetooth module hears something...
  if (BTSerial.available()) {
    // Read the character!
    char command = BTSerial.read();

    // Check what the character is
    if (command == 'F') {
      moveForward();
    } 
    else if (command == 'S') {
      stopCar();
    }
    // Add more if/else statements for B, L, R!
  }
}

Creating the Helper Functions
To keep our code clean, we use custom functions like moveForward().
void moveForward() {
  // Left Motor Forward
  digitalWrite(IN1, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(IN2, LOW);

  // Right Motor Forward
  digitalWrite(IN3, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(IN4, LOW);
}

void stopCar() {
  digitalWrite(IN1, LOW);
  digitalWrite(IN2, LOW);
  digitalWrite(IN3, LOW);
  digitalWrite(IN4, LOW);
}

Connecting with Dabble
To make the Arduino talk to the Dabble app, we just need to include the library and start it in our code. Dabble automatically knows to use Pins 2 and 3!
#define CUSTOM_SETTINGS
#define INCLUDE_GAMEPAD_MODULE
#include &lt;Dabble.h&gt;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600); 
  Dabble.begin(9600); // Start Bluetooth communication
}

Reading the Gamepad
In our loop(), we need to continuously check if the Dabble app is sending any button presses:
void loop() {
  Dabble.processInput(); // Refresh data from the smartphone

  if (GamePad.isUpPressed()) {
    moveForward();
  } 
  else if (GamePad.isDownPressed()) {
    moveBackward(); // Assuming we have this function
  }
  else if (GamePad.isLeftPressed()) {
    moveLeft(); // Assuming we have this function
  }
  else if (GamePad.isRightPressed()) {
    moveRight(); // Assuming we have this function
  }
  else {
    stopCar();
  }
}

Coding the Servo: Setup
Arduino has a built-in library for Servos! We don’t have to control the exact electrical pulses manually.
#include &lt;Servo.h&gt;  // Include the library

Servo myServo;  // Create a servo object

void setup() {
  myServo.attach(9); // Tell Arduino the servo is on pin 9
}

void loop() {
  // We'll add angles here
}

Pointing at Angles 📐
To make it point, we use myServo.write(angle). The angle is between 0 and 180.
void loop() {
  myServo.write(0);      // Turn all the way right
  delay(1000);           // Wait 1 second

  myServo.write(90);     // Turn to the middle
  delay(1000);

  myServo.write(180);    // Turn all the way left
  delay(1000);
}
Activity: Let’s wire this up and try making it point in 3 directions!

The “Sweep” 🧹
What if we want it to move smoothly from 0 to 180? We use a for loop to increase the angle slowly.
void loop() {
  // Sweep from 0 to 180 degrees
  for (int pos = 0; pos &lt;= 180; pos += 1) { 
    myServo.write(pos);              
    delay(15); // Wait 15ms for servo to reach position                      
  }
}

Coding Distance: The Logic
const int trigPin = 10;
const int echoPin = 11;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600); // Start serial monitor
  pinMode(trigPin, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(echoPin, INPUT);
}

void loop() {
  // We will add the logic here!
}

Coding Distance: The Math
void loop() {
  // Send a 10 microsecond pulse
  digitalWrite(trigPin, LOW);
  delayMicroseconds(2);
  digitalWrite(trigPin, HIGH);
  delayMicroseconds(10);
  digitalWrite(trigPin, LOW);

  // Measure how long the Echo pin stays HIGH
  long duration = pulseIn(echoPin, HIGH);

  // Calculate distance in cm (Speed of sound)
  int distance = duration * 0.034 / 2;

  Serial.print("Distance: ");
  Serial.print(distance);
  Serial.println(" cm");

  delay(500);
}

